As a starting point, any development concept, retail or otherwise, is most defensible when it would directly advance a public economic or social policy objective that a private pro forma would not produce on its own. 
A residual land value analysis provides government officials with that answer. From there, planners and policymakers would need to determine whether investing in the project supports a public good or benefit that outweighs the potential economic headwinds the development could face in the future. 
In the apartment uplift analysis, the residential units would pay a premium rent because of the presence of retail, so they wouldn’t quality as affordable housing. But government officials might argue that new housing at elevated prices would help with supply, perhaps through filtering, and that the public interest would also be served by the tax revenue the development would provide, which would justify investment of public funds.
I would not support such an argument. In my view, the housing crisis has reached a stage where subsidies for affordable housing must take precedence over subsidies that would support market-rate units. With the difficulties office real estate has endured in the post-pandemic market, I would not support subsidies for an office component to a mixed-income plan. I would prioritize subsidies for affordable housing and, specifically, to provide affordable housing in an economically advantageous area, especially one that is near transit stations and an employment center.
